#Assume you're given a table containing job postings from various companies on the LinkedIn platform. Write a query to retrieve 
#the count of companies that have posted duplicate job listings.

Select count(company_id) as duplicate_companies from job_listings group by (select count(DISTINCT(title))>1 from job_listings);


#Using the GROUP BY clause to group all rows by the target column(s) – i.e. the column(s) you want to check for duplicate values on. Using 
#the COUNT function in the HAVING clause to check if any of the groups have more than 1 entry; those would be the duplicate values.
